We may note by the way, that the slighter convulsions, like those twitchings of the tendons which trouble many in continued severs, may to some extent arise from a diseased condition of the muscular flesh, in so lar as not only the saline-sulphureous but also the nitro-aeria] particles passing through the now nearly wasted away parenchyma ol the flesh, are transmitted into the motor parts, and by their mutual effervescente the often slight contractioris ol the fibrils are, as is likely, produced.

From what has been said, the reason can be given why bodily exercises are so useful in the icteric disease and scorbutus, and also for warding off the paroxyms of intermittent severs. For in exercise the nitro-aerial particles are sent in greater abundante into the mass of the blood by the more intense respiration, and the motion of the blood is much promoted by the contractiori of the muscles; whence it comes about that the fermentation ol the blood is increased and it is comminuted and worked up. F urther, the saline-sulphureous particles brought to vigour are secreted from the blood and used up in muscular contraction‚ and it is by their excess in the mass ol the blood that febrile heat is excited, as has been elsewhere said.
